        <div class=\"row\">
            <div class=\"col-lg-8\">
                <p>
                    In 1938 / 1939, Volkswagen GmbH, which had been founded a year earlier, set up its plant near Fallersleben 
                    in what is today Wolfsburg. After the start of the war, cars were not produced there for the German civilian 
                    population as originally planned, but instead armaments orders were taken on. The Volkswagen Group also made 
                    use of the various forms of National Socialist forced labor. By the end of 1944, forced laborers made up two 
                    thirds of the workforce; in total, some 200,000 persons were compelled to perform forced labor at Volkswagen, 
                    many of whom did not survive the working conditions. In addition to civilian forced laborers, Soviet prisoners 
                    of war and Italian military internees, this also included a total of about 5,000 concentration camp inmates. 
                    After the history of the VW Group under National Socialism had become the subject of extensive public discussion 
                    and academic research in the 1980s and 1990s, the VW plant today accommodates a memorial to forced labor on 
                    the site.<sup><a href=\"#endnote7\" id=\"footnote7\">7</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Compared to other concentration camp prisoners, the 300er Group at the VW plant was relatively well looked after. 
                    Even though they did not receive new clothes, they were protected from the weather by their accommodation. 
                    Although set too low for the work required of them, food rations were more extensive than in other camps. 
                    The symptoms of malnutrition typical of many concentration camps, which often led to the death of the prisoners in 
                    the long term, did not initially occur in the 300er Group.<sup><a href=\"#endnote8\" id=\"footnote8\">8</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Due to the prisoners’ training and intended function, the SS and VW initially had an interest in their survival, 
                    but this only extended to the duration of the war and the associated necessity of underground V1 production. 
                    After the war, survivors testified in interviews or memoirs that after their experiences in Auschwitz-Birkenau 
                    and the subsequent concentration camps, in retrospect their time at the Volkswagen factory seemed bearable by 
                    comparison.<sup><a href=\"#endnote9\" id=\"footnote9\">9</a></sup>
                </p>
