                    the attack in a bunker, after a few days the Group was deported from the completely destroyed factory to another 
                    production facility in occupied France. On their way to the camp, which was located in occupied Lorraine, 
                    the Group learned of the Allied landing in Normandy. According to survivor David Hollander, the confirmation 
                    of this news was “the happiest moment” during his imprisonment in a concentration 
                    camp.<sup><a href=\"#endnote10\" id=\"footnote10\">10</a></sup> In Thil, they also met up again with the 
                    Group of 500 men who had been selected together with them in Auschwitz-Birkenau. Here, too, the 300 men were 
                    isolated. Survivors reported that they had to set up their own barracks camp, including a crematorium, which 
                    was separated from the other prisoners by a fence.<sup><a href=\"#endnote11\" id=\"footnote11\">11</a></sup>
                    During the selections, the men had often been separated from friends and relatives, some of whom they now saw 
                    again through the fence. However, any contact was strictly prosecuted. Survivor Eliesar Farkas, among others, 
                    reported that a prisoner in the other group had recognized his brother and sought a conversation with him at 
                    the fence, whereupon he was shot.<sup><a href=\"#endnote12\" id=\"footnote12\">12</a></sup> Survivor Alex Rosenbaum, 
                    on the other hand, managed to secretly exchange a few words with his father in the other camp.<sup><a href=\"#endnote13\" id=\"footnote13\">13</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    As the production facility in Thil had not yet been completed, the Group was mainly used for clearing and 
                    construction work, despite their extensive training. The Group was also regularly sent to a nearby French village. 
                    Despite being guarded, prisoners there managed to make contact with the French civilian population and the French 
                    resistance movement, the Résistance. Survivors such as Pal Arie testified that one prisoner was even able to 
                    escape with the help of the French Résistance and was taken through the front lines to the US Army, where he was 
                    able to report on the V1 production.<sup><a href=\"#endnote14\" id=\"footnote14\">14</a></sup>
                    The US Army was able to liberate Paris at the end of August. Long before production could begin in Thil, the 
                    satellite camp was evacuated at the beginning of September 1944 as the Allies approached.
                </p>
