                    Bergen-Belsen concentration camp in freight and cattle cars. The prisoners, already weakened, were not cared 
                    for during the transport, which lasted several days, so that the majority of them did not survive the journey. 
                    Survivor Moshe Shen testified that 100 people were accommodated in his railroad car, only 20 of whom survived 
                    the ten-day journey.<sup><a href=\"#endnote21\" id=\"footnote21\">21</a></sup> 
                    According to estimates, up to 8,000 prisoners did not survive the evacuation transports and death marches from 
                    Mittelbau-Dora.<sup><a href=\"#endnote22\" id=\"footnote22\">22</a></sup>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The supply situation in the completely overcrowded Bergen-Belsen camp was disastrous, so that more inmates from 
                    the 300er Group were probably murdered there due to the conditions of detention. The approximately 15,000 
                    prisoners from Mittelbau-Dora who arrived in Bergen-Belsen in April 1945 were quartered in former Wehrmacht 
                    barracks, the so-called barracks camp.<sup><a href=\"#endnote23\" id=\"footnote23\">23</a></sup> The surviving prisoners 
                    of the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp were liberated there on April 15, 1945 by British troops, who took over 
                    the concentration camp without a fight.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Upon liberation, the Allies found over 53,000 prisoners starving to death and countless others already dead. 
                    Many thousands continued to die after liberation as a result of their imprisonment. By June 1945 alone, 14,000 
                    former prisoners from Bergen-Belsen had lost their lives. The British troops were not prepared for the appalling 
                    conditions they encountered in Bergen-Belsen. Many prisoners perished, not least because their starving stomachs 
                    could not cope with the food generously distributed by the British soldiers at the beginning. Only after a few 
                    days did the necessary light food arrive.<sup><a href=\"#endnote24\" id=\"footnote24\">24</a></sup>
                    Survivor Moshe Shen recalled that he was too weak at the time of liberation to meet the British and accept the food 
                    that was distributed, which probably saved his life.<sup><a href=\"#endnote25\" id=\"footnote25\">25</a></sup>
                </p>
