                <p class=\"caption\">
                    Excerpt from the list of assigned Buchenwald concentration camp inmate numbers for arrivals from Natzweiler 
                    concentration camp (Rebstock satellite camp), September 27, 1944 and from Dachau concentration camp, 
                    September 30, 1944. Ghetto Fighters’ House Archives, 2608, Collection Section Lists of inmates in the 
                    Buchenwald Camp, Germany.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The data they contain illustrates the difficulties in dealing with documents from the concentration camp 
                    administration. For example, the occupations provided by the prisoners are listed. However, these were given 
                    with regard to the selection in Auschwitz and often do not correspond to the persons’ actual occupations. 
                    The profession of journalist Dezső Schön, for example, is given as “fitter.” Dates of birth were also sometimes 
                    deliberately given incorrectly in order to avoid being murdered by the SS. Moshe Shen, Dezső Schön’s son, 
                    claimed to be 20 years old, although he was actually only 14, in order to be classified as fit for work. The 
                    lists were also usually kept by other prisoners who were deployed in the administration. These prisoners 
                    frequently did not speak Hungarian and they were also subjected to inhumane conditions of detention, so the 
                    documents they kept were often incorrect. A comparison of the two lists shows that only 62 of the 298 people 
                    were documented with identical names and data. In particular, merely a fraction of the Hungarian first names 
                    were recorded in the same spelling.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Only because the Group was isolated and deported together has it been possible to assign the different data 
                    to the same persons. In the case of other prisoners, who were usually distributed to satellite camps via main 
                    camps, for example Neuengamme, it is often much more difficult to assign different data due to the gaps in 
                    the records. In addition to documents that were destroyed, administrative records were often no longer kept, 
                    especially in the final months of the war. One can therefore assume that the names of the prisoners from 
                    Mittelbau-Dora who arrived in Bergen-Belsen in April were no longer recorded. The same applies to those who 
                    perished during transportation, for example. Many victims thus remain nameless. We owe our knowledge of the 
                    prisoners’ routes, work assignments, and conditions of detention above all to the reports and testimonies of 
                    the survivors.
                </p>
